Class: CS-451: "Operating Systems"
Assignment: Project 4
Date: 17 March 2026
Author: Samantha Robinson, Elizabeth Sullivan
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
This program simulates a taxi pickup system using POSIX threads and semaphores to model synchronization between students and taxis. Each student thread represents a student 
attending a party for a random amount of time and then waiting for a taxi. Taxi threads repeatedly arrive at a curb and pick up students in groups of four. A circular queue is 
used to manage the order of waiting students, ensuring that students are picked up in the order they finish partying. Semaphores are used to enforce mutual exclusion on the 
queue, coordinate when students are ready, and ensure that only one taxi can occupy the curb at a time. Students signal when they are ready to be picked up, and taxis wait 
until four students are available before departing. After each trip, taxis signal the corresponding students that their ride is complete. The program continues until all 
students have been picked up and taken home. Input validation ensures that the number of students is divisible by four and within the allowed limits. All project requirements 
are met: the use of pthreads, semaphores, synchronization constraints, command-line arguments, and proper thread termination.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The program can be used as follows from the terminal: 
To compile (if necessary):
gcc -o Party main.c TaxiAndStudentFunctions.c -lpthread
To run: 
./Party -s 12 -t 3 -m 15
